(v_mod1, 'Which type of foreclosure buyer is best suited for auction purchases?', '["First-time homebuyers with FHA financing", "Investors with cash and rehab experience", "Move-up buyers coordinating a simultaneous sale", "Bargain hunters with limited budgets"]', 1, 5);


-- =============================================
-- MODULE 2: Pre-Foreclosure and Short Sale Purchases
-- =============================================
INSERT INTO course_modules (title, section, description, tier, sort_order, course_id)
VALUES (
  'Pre-Foreclosure and Short Sale Purchases',
  'Pre-Foreclosure Buying',
  'Learn how to identify and navigate pre-foreclosure opportunities. Understand the buyer''s role in short sale transactions, how to write competitive offers, and how to manage the extended timelines involved.',
  'free',
  2,
  v_course_id
) RETURNING id INTO v_mod2;

INSERT INTO course_lessons (id, module_id, title, content, sort_order) VALUES
('fp-2-1', v_mod2, 'Understanding the Pre-Foreclosure Window', E'# Understanding the Pre-Foreclosure Window\n\nThe pre-foreclosure period is the window between when a homeowner defaults on their mortgage and when the property goes to auction. For buyers, this window represents an opportunity to purchase a property through a negotiated sale — often at below-market value — while avoiding the risks of an auction.\n\n## What Triggers Pre-Foreclosure\n\nPre-foreclosure begins when the lender files a public notice indicating the borrower is in default:\n\n- **Judicial states:** The lender files a **lis pendens** (notice of pending litigation) with the court\n- **Non-judicial states:** The lender records a **notice of default** with the county recorder\n\nBoth filings are **public records**, meaning anyone can find properties in pre-foreclosure by searching county records or using foreclosure listing services.\n\n## The Pre-Foreclosure Timeline\n\nThe length of the pre-foreclosure window varies significantly:\n\n- **Non-judicial states (like Texas):** The window can be as short as **21-60 days** from the notice of default to the auction\n- **Judicial states (like New York):** The process can take **12-36 months** through the court system\n- **During COVID-related moratoriums:** The window was extended significantly in many states\n\nThis timeline determines how much time buyers and agents have to negotiate a purchase.\n\n## Types of Pre-Foreclosure Purchases\n\n### 1. Direct Purchase from the Homeowner\nIf the homeowner has equity (the property is worth more than the mortgage balance), they can sell the property before the auction:\n\n- The sale pays off the mortgage, any liens, and closing costs\n- The homeowner keeps any remaining proceeds\n- This is essentially a **traditional sale under time pressure**\n- The buyer can use normal financing and conduct inspections\n- The homeowner avoids foreclosure on their credit record\n\n### 2. Short Sale\nIf the homeowner is underwater (owes more than the property is worth), they need lender approval to sell for less than the mortgage balance:\n\n- The lender must approve the sale price and terms\n- The process adds weeks or months to the timeline\n- The buyer must be patient — lender approval is not guaranteed\n- The buyer can typically inspect the property and use financing\n\n### 3. Assumption or Subject-To Purchase\nIn some cases, a buyer may purchase the property by assuming the existing mortgage or buying \"subject to\" the existing loan:\n\n- **Assumption:** The buyer formally takes over the seller''s mortgage (requires lender approval)\n- **Subject-to:** The buyer takes title while the original mortgage stays in the seller''s name\n- These are **advanced strategies** typically used by experienced investors\n- They carry unique legal and financial risks\n- Most traditional buyers and their agents should avoid these unless they have specialized expertise\n\n## Finding Pre-Foreclosure Properties\n\n### Public Records\n- Search county recorder or clerk of court websites for lis pendens and notice of default filings\n- Many counties have online databases that are searchable by date, address, or owner name\n- These records include the property address, owner name, lender, and filing date\n\n### Foreclosure Listing Services\n- Services like RealtyTrac, Foreclosure.com, and PropertyShark compile pre-foreclosure filings\n- These services charge subscription fees but save significant research time\n- Verify all information independently — databases may be outdated\n\n### Agent Networks\n- Connect with listing agents who work with distressed sellers\n- Short sale specialists often know of properties before they hit the market\n- Bankruptcy and divorce attorneys may refer clients who need to sell quickly\n\n## Approaching Pre-Foreclosure Sellers\n\nIf your buyer is interested in contacting pre-foreclosure homeowners directly, proceed with extreme caution:\n\n### Legal Restrictions\n- Many states have **Home Equity Sales Contract Acts** or similar laws that protect homeowners in foreclosure\n- These laws may require specific disclosures, cooling-off periods, and prohibit certain practices\n- Some states restrict contact with homeowners once a foreclosure notice is filed\n- Violations can result in the sale being voided, fines, and legal liability\n\n### Ethical Guidelines\n- Never pressure or take advantage of a distressed homeowner\n- Be transparent about who you are and what you are proposing\n- Recommend that the homeowner consult with their own attorney\n- Do not make promises about stopping the foreclosure or guaranteeing outcomes\n- Treat every homeowner with dignity and respect\n\n### Best Practices\n- Work through the homeowner''s listing agent if they have one\n- If approaching directly, send a respectful letter rather than showing up unannounced\n- Clearly state your buyer''s interest and qualifications\n- Allow the homeowner time to consider and seek advice\n- Document all communications\n\n## Advantages of Pre-Foreclosure Purchases for Buyers\n\n1. **Better condition:** The homeowner is still living in (and usually maintaining) the property\n2. **Inspection rights:** Buyers can conduct full inspections\n3. **Title clarity:** Title searches can be completed before closing\n4. **Financing options:** Standard mortgage financing is typically available\n5. **Negotiation:** Motivated sellers may accept below-market offers\n6. **Less competition:** Fewer buyers search pre-foreclosure listings compared to MLS\n\n## Risks of Pre-Foreclosure Purchases\n\n1. **Timeline uncertainty:** Short sales can take months; the auction date may arrive first\n2. **Lender approval required:** In short sales, the lender can reject the sale\n3. **Emotional sellers:** Distressed homeowners may be difficult to work with\n4. **Hidden liens:** Tax liens, judgment liens, or second mortgages may complicate the title\n5. **Property condition:** Stressed homeowners may have deferred maintenance\n6. **Legal complexity:** State laws, lender requirements, and disclosure obligations add layers of complexity\n\n## Summary\n\nThe pre-foreclosure window offers buyers the opportunity to purchase properties through negotiated sales with significant advantages over auction purchases. However, these transactions require patience, sensitivity, and a thorough understanding of the legal and practical considerations involved.', 1),

('fp-2-2', v_mod2, 'Representing Buyers in Short Sale Transactions', E'# Representing Buyers in Short Sale Transactions\n\nWhen your buyer finds a short sale they want to purchase, your role shifts from property finder to transaction manager and expectations counselor. Short sales test the patience of everyone involved, and the buyer''s agent is often the glue that holds the deal together.\n\n## How Short Sales Differ from the Buyer''s Perspective\n\nFrom your buyer''s point of view, a short sale is different from a traditional purchase in several critical ways:\n\n### 1. The Seller Cannot Accept Your Offer\nUnlike a traditional sale where the seller can accept or reject an offer, in a short sale the seller can only **forward** the offer to the lender. The lender makes the final decision. Your buyer is really negotiating with the bank, not the homeowner.\n\n### 2. The Timeline Is Extended\nAfter offer submission, expect to wait **30-120 days** (sometimes longer) for the lender to respond. During this time:\n- The lender reviews the seller''s financial package\n- The lender orders a BPO (Broker Price Opinion) or appraisal\n- The lender evaluates the net proceeds against their foreclosure recovery estimate\n- If there are multiple lienholders, each must independently approve\n\n### 3. The Lender May Counter\nThe lender may come back with a counter-offer that requires a higher price. Your buyer needs to decide whether the property is still worth it at the higher number.\n\n### 4. Nothing Is Guaranteed\nThe lender can reject the short sale at any time, and the seller can be foreclosed on during the process, effectively killing your buyer''s deal.\n\n## Writing a Strong Short Sale Offer\n\nA well-crafted offer increases the chances of lender approval and sets your buyer up for success.\n\n### Offer Price\n- Base your offer on a thorough CMA — the lender will compare your offer to their own valuation\n- Lowball offers waste everyone''s time — the lender will reject them outright\n- Consider that the lender is comparing your offer to their estimated foreclosure recovery\n- An offer at **85-95% of market value** is typically competitive for short sales\n\n### Financing\n- Cash offers are strongest — they close fastest and have the fewest contingencies\n- Conventional financing is preferred over FHA/VA by most lenders (fewer repair requirements)\n- Include a strong pre-approval letter from a reputable lender\n- Higher earnest money deposits show seriousness\n\n### Contingencies\n- Keep contingencies minimal — excessive contingencies weaken the offer\n- Inspection contingency: Include it, but set a short timeline and be realistic about as-is condition\n- Financing contingency: Shorten the timeline if possible\n- Appraisal contingency: Consider waiving if your buyer has funds to cover a gap\n\n### Short Sale Addendum\nAlways include a short sale addendum that addresses:\n- The offer is subject to lender approval\n- The buyer has the right to continue searching for other properties\n- A maximum waiting period before the buyer can withdraw without penalty\n- What happens if the lender counters on price\n- Responsibility for any association dues, taxes, or assessments during the waiting period\n\n### Supporting Documentation\nSubmit with your offer:\n- Buyer''s pre-approval letter or proof of funds\n- A brief letter explaining why your buyer is a strong candidate (cash, flexible timeline, etc.)\n- Your CMA supporting the offer price\n\n## Managing the Waiting Period\n\nThe waiting period is where most short sale deals fall apart — not because of the lender, but because of the buyer.\n\n### Keep Your Buyer Engaged\n- Call your buyer weekly with updates, even if there is nothing new\n- Explain what the lender is doing at each stage (reviewing docs, ordering BPO, awaiting investor approval)\n- Let your buyer know that silence is normal — it does not mean bad news\n- Share stories of successful short sale closings to maintain confidence\n\n### Continue Shopping\n- Always advise your buyer to continue looking at other properties\n- If they find a better option, they can withdraw from the short sale\n- Having a backup plan reduces anxiety and prevents impulsive decisions\n\n### Monitor the Foreclosure Timeline\n- If the property is headed toward auction, the short sale timeline may be cut short\n- Ask the listing agent about the foreclosure status regularly\n- In many cases, the lender will postpone the auction while reviewing a short sale, but this is not guaranteed\n\n### Stay in Touch with the Listing Agent\n- The listing agent is your best source of information on lender communications\n- Check in at least weekly\n- Offer to provide any additional documentation the lender requests\n- Be a cooperative partner, not a demanding adversary\n\n## When the Lender Responds\n\n### Approval\nIf the lender approves the short sale:\n- Review the approval letter carefully with your buyer\n- Note the approved price, closing deadline, and any conditions\n- Move quickly — approval letters typically have **30-60 day expiration dates**\n- Schedule inspections immediately (if not already completed)\n- Ensure your buyer''s financing is current and ready to close\n\n### Counter-Offer\nIf the lender counters at a higher price:\n- Run the numbers — is the property still a good value at the counter price?\n- Check comparable sales to validate the lender''s counter\n- Negotiate if there is room, but understand the lender has a floor based on the BPO\n- Decide quickly — delays can restart the review process\n\n### Rejection\nIf the lender rejects the short sale:\n- Ask the listing agent why — the reason determines next steps\n- If the BPO was too high, request a resubmission after a new BPO\n- If the net was too low, the buyer may need to increase the offer\n- If the lender prefers foreclosure, there may be an opportunity to buy the property as an REO later\n\n## Common Short Sale Pitfalls for Buyers\n\n1. **Falling in love with the property** — emotional attachment during a 4-month wait leads to poor decisions\n2. **Losing financing** — pre-approvals expire; interest rates change; buyer''s financial situation shifts\n3. **Missing the closing deadline** — approval letters expire; extensions are not always granted\n4. **Underestimating repairs** — as-is condition plus deferred maintenance equals surprise costs\n5. **Not reading the approval letter** — conditions, deficiency terms, and deadlines can create issues\n\n## Summary\n\nRepresenting buyers in short sales requires patience, proactive communication, and a deep understanding of the lender approval process. Agents who manage expectations, submit strong offers, and maintain engagement throughout the waiting period successfully guide their buyers to closing.', 2),

('fp-2-3', v_mod2, 'Pre-Foreclosure Due Diligence', E'# Pre-Foreclosure Due Diligence\n\nDue diligence on pre-foreclosure and short sale properties is even more critical than on traditional purchases. The distressed nature of the property and the seller''s financial situation create additional risks that your buyer must understand and investigate.\n\n## Title Research\n\nTitle is the most important area of due diligence for any foreclosure-related purchase.\n\n### What to Search For\n- **First mortgage balance and lender** — who holds the primary mortgage?\n- **Second mortgages and HELOCs** — junior liens that must be resolved\n- **Tax liens** — unpaid property taxes create senior liens that survive foreclosure\n- **HOA/COA liens** — unpaid association dues\n- **Judgment liens** — court judgments against the property owner\n- **Mechanic''s liens** — unpaid contractor work on the property\n- **IRS liens** — federal tax liens can complicate title clearance\n- **Code enforcement liens** — municipal fines for property violations\n\n### Why Title Matters\nIn a pre-foreclosure purchase, you have the advantage of conducting a full title search before closing. This is a significant advantage over auction purchases where title issues may not be discovered until after the sale.\n\n### Getting Title Work Done\n- Order a preliminary title report as early as possible\n- Use a title company experienced with distressed property transactions\n- Review the title commitment carefully for exceptions and requirements\n- Ensure title insurance will cover any known issues\n- Resolve lien issues before closing — this is the listing agent and seller''s responsibility, but verify independently\n\n## Property Inspection\n\n### Why Inspections Are Critical\nDistressed properties are more likely to have maintenance issues because:\n- Homeowners facing financial hardship often defer maintenance\n- Vacant properties deteriorate faster (plumbing freezes, pests, vandalism)\n- Distressed sellers may have attempted DIY repairs that are not code-compliant\n- Insurance may have lapsed, leaving damage unrepaired\n\n### What to Inspect\n\n**Standard Home Inspection:**\n- Structure and foundation\n- Roof and exterior\n- Plumbing and electrical systems\n- HVAC systems\n- Interior finishes and fixtures\n- Appliances (if present)\n\n**Additional Inspections to Consider:**\n- **Sewer line scope** — clogged or damaged sewer lines are common in distressed properties\n- **Mold inspection** — especially if the property has been vacant or had water damage\n- **Termite and pest inspection** — required in many states; especially important for properties with deferred maintenance\n- **Foundation inspection** — if the standard inspection reveals signs of movement\n- **Environmental assessments** — for older homes, check for asbestos, lead paint, or underground storage tanks\n- **Pool inspection** — if the property has a pool, verify equipment, shell condition, and compliance\n\n### Inspection Strategy for Short Sales\nSince short sales have extended timelines, consider the timing of inspections:\n\n**Option 1: Inspect Before Lender Approval**\n- Pros: Buyer knows the condition early; can walk away before investing more time\n- Cons: Buyer pays for inspection on a property that may not be approved\n- Best for: Properties with obvious condition concerns\n\n**Option 2: Inspect After Lender Approval**\n- Pros: Buyer only pays for inspection on an approved deal\n- Cons: Discovering major issues at this stage leaves little time to decide\n- Best for: Properties in apparently good condition\n\n**Recommendation:** For most short sales, inspect early. The $400-600 cost of an inspection is a small price compared to months of waiting for a property that turns out to need $50,000 in repairs.\n\n## Financial Analysis\n\n### The Numbers Must Work\nFor every foreclosure or pre-foreclosure purchase, create a detailed financial analysis:\n\n**Purchase Cost Worksheet:**\n- Purchase price: $________\n- Closing costs (estimated at 2-5%): $________\n- Immediate repair costs: $________\n- Cosmetic updates: $________\n- Contingency (10-20% of repair budget): $________\n- **Total investment:** $________\n\n**Value Analysis:**\n- Current as-is market value: $________\n- Estimated after-repair value (ARV): $________\n- Comparable rental income (if investment): $________/month\n\n**For owner-occupants:** Total investment should be at or below the ARV\n**For investors (buy and hold):** Monthly rent should cover PITI + maintenance + vacancy reserve + management\n**For investors (flip):** ARV minus total investment should equal target profit (typically 15-20% minimum)\n\n### Red Flags in the Numbers\n- Repair costs that eliminate the foreclosure discount\n- Property taxes or HOA dues significantly higher than expected\n- Market values declining in the area\n- Comparable properties sitting on the market for extended periods\n- Rental rates that do not support the investment for buy-and-hold buyers\n\n## Occupancy Status\n\nDetermine who is currently living in the property:\n\n### Owner-Occupied\n- The homeowner is still living in the property\n- Access for inspections and showings is typically available\n- The homeowner is expected to maintain the property during the transaction\n- Move-out coordination is part of the closing process\n\n### Tenant-Occupied\n- Tenants may have rights that survive the sale (depending on state law and lease terms)\n- Federal and state laws may require honoring existing leases\n- Evicting tenants adds time and cost\n- Tenant cooperation for access may be limited\n\n### Vacant\n- No occupancy issues, but the property may deteriorate faster\n- Verify utilities are active for inspections\n- Check for vandalism, theft, or unauthorized occupants\n- Winterization may be needed in cold climates\n\n## Summary\n\nDue diligence on pre-foreclosure properties requires thorough title research, comprehensive inspections, careful financial analysis, and verification of occupancy status. Agents who invest time in proper due diligence protect their buyers from the hidden risks that make foreclosure purchases different from traditional transactions.', 3);

